description.plain:
“Uh Huh” is a song by the American country-influenced singer-songwriter Jade Bird, released on August 3, 2018 and eventually included in her first self-titled studio album.

This breakthrough single has established a de-attachment from Jade’s previous songs: in fact, here she’s not singing with remorse and melancholy about his ex, like she did in “Lottery”.
She’d rather go fiery in order to have revenge on her past: his ex is treated by his new girlfriend as a toy, exactly as he did with Jade.

This stylistic transformation is accentuated by a more energetic instrumental, which has always been desired to be recreated by the young singer:


“I’m little, I’m 5'3, but I always sound very fussy. And I really wanted to show this more fiery side.”

“I have always been obsessed with that raw, band-in-a-room sound, and I am so happy with the result. It’s got an attitude that is a big part of who I am, and what I write about.”


The track, reminiscent of classics about toxic relationships like “You Oughta Know”, can also be interpreted as a state of female empowerment: Jade has never hidden her determination to spread a positive message for herself and other young girls, as she declared to Harper’s Bazaar:

“I think the importance comes from the importance of having strong females in my life, full stop. I was pretty much brought up by mom and grandma, who were both single parents. My mum was always listening to the diva of the time, you know, Avril Lavigne, Pink, etcetera. I think she just inspired this mentality that I am good enough… just quite a strong feminist sentiment.
I’m attracted to strong women doing their craft, be it in that amazing person, Kate Moross, who I work with, or Alanis Morissette, or Phoebe Bridgers. I’m attracted to that non-apologetic kind of ‘I’m going to do my thing because I just think it’s a very unique thing’. I want to inspire girls who don’t want to hide behind their guitars and write sad songs. You’ve kind of got to be out there, a bit more confident, a little bit. I’d love to inspire young girls to feel like that.”

annotations:
Does she wake up, put on make-up in the bathroom
 And go to work, and stay real late and text you she’ll be back soon?
 But her boss runs his fingers ’round her pretty blonde platinum ’do
 I bet you never thought about that, did you?

As the topic is the aftermath of the breakup from a toxic relationship and the song presents stylistic similarities with “You Oughta Know” by Alanis Morissette (not surprisingly quoted by Bird herself as one of the most significant role models while growing up), it’s quite simple to make a connection between the lyrics of both the tracks.

In fact, in “You Oughta Know” Morissette interrogates her ex about his new soul-mate’s maturity and… sexual overtures:

An older version of me
Is she perverted like me?
Would she go down on you in a theater?
Does she speak eloquently
And would she have your baby?
I’m sure she’d make a really excellent mother

That was a clear accuse to him, guilty of not considering Alanis and forcing her to “go wild” and have kids against her will.

Jade uses a similar format to build the first verse of “Uh Huh”, even though her accuses are less hard: she makes references at the (lower) maturity of her substitute in love as well, but she also wants to have her revenge on him: is there another type of start better than evoking the ghost of an embarrassing love triangle?

description.plain:
“Now is the Time” is the fifth single and tenth track on Jade Bird’s sophomore album, Different Kinds of Light. The song has an upbeat tone and optimistic lyrics, telling the story of two lovers committed to staying side-by-side through thick and thin.

The day of its release, Bird said on BBC Radio 1 that the Bee Gees‘ Barry Gibb helped inspire her to triple-track the vocals on the song in order to produce a stronger sound, something she’d never tried.

annotations:
I was 19 and you were 23 and
 We stayed in Number 4 Ferdinand Street
 We spent five talking ’bout our lives
 But we’d talked like that about a thousand times
 And I’m bored of all that

Two lovers have reconnected after some time apart. They talk about their lives for a few minutes, but the Narrator is uninterested in that. Instead, she recounts something he once said about love being a lottery. It seems to have stuck with her, as she is still preoccupied with numbers:  19, 23, 4, 5, and 1,000 just in verse one.
Jade Bird said that #4, Ferdinand Street is a blues bar she grew up playing in since the age of sixteen.

description.plain:
Something American is the opening track of Jade Bird’s debut EP with the same name. Via Facebook, Jade wrote about the song:

“Something American is the title and name to a very special opening track. I’ve had the total pleasure to record this in Upstate NYC. Near Woodstock for the Brits, Palenville to the New Yorkers. I’ve felt insanely lucky, grateful and almost entirely undeserving of the whole experience! Safe in the love of ‘real’ music cockney accent (you know like proper drums?). With the help of Matt Johnson, Jesske Hume, David Baron and the incredible, now, good friend of mine Simone Felice we’ve really gone to town on this.”

It also compares the breakdown of the traditional American relationship with the breakdown of an actual relationship.

annotations: Jade Bird’s music is often characterized as “Americana”- ironic considering that she is English. Jade Bird is using “American” the same way- as a sort of modern Romantic ideal for the average person. High school sweethearts are an example of this.

I can feel you all night
 In my dreams I find
 The stars align and they all collide
 And it’s you and I
 Oh, back in time, it feels so right
Jade it nostalgic about the relationship, the time they shared and the way they felt.

I’m not nice like her
 Won’t wear white like her
 Don’t live life with the pages mapped out
 No, I’m not perfect
 But then no one is

Jade is not up to the expected standards. The other girl fulfils the stereotype of what a relationship ‘should be’. By being ‘boring’.

Jade is annoyed that all this stuff even matters. No one is perfect! It’s not important, but to him and his heritage, it is.
We’re all reaching for something American
Reaching for something America is part of the problem. She can feel he’s lonely even though he’s not calling.

We knew each other when we were very young
 High school sweethearts, or something American
Candidly commenting on the idea that high school sweethearts are no longer relevant. Bitter that an American girl has taken her place.
